<subSubSection id="714D3749860080C18223B3DF34E141D5" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" type="distribution and ecology">
<paragraph id="6EA6CC79516E4F64E8EE9628ACB2B08E" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E90FA668170C164A753049FE9871BF8B" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Known only from the Andes of Venezuela (Lara, Portuguesa, and Trujillo states) where it is found in the understory of montane and cloud forest; 1900-2800 m.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A8C5326D655342E2AC7321895FEB8315" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="3DF1A89325BBF0DC0505282232A89B70" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BCB346D2FCA14D6A2E67A995AE753844" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">This species is named for Nicholas Dorr who assisted with field work in the Venezuelan Andes, but clearly prefers the rigors of Chichiriviche to those of the mountains.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
