<subSubSection id="9243411B3D9FB94C04E4EDA8C26AFC81" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="62" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="00D3E8A859BDCAEAF51E4B9B32A0454F" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6E5121571C9F7922CDD4747D5B3A384D" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">
The majority of collections of 
<taxonomicName id="4423D11FF85BEBDBE4097AECDA35104C" authorityName="Dorr &amp; Stergios" authorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea nicholasii" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nicholasii">
<emphasis id="5CF0728556F76BF978E7C6017BA2BEE6" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Pilea nicholasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have either staminate or pistillate inflorescences on a stem. Several collections, including the type (
<emphasis id="6AD80E96F2C41CA6B289E249FF774B92" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Stergios &amp; Dorr 20208</emphasis>
), however, have both staminate and pistillate inflorescences on the same stem, and at least one collection (
<emphasis id="D7A70CEADCDA7361C3607A5C783817C3" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Cuello et al. 1416</emphasis>
) has both staminate and pistillate inflorescences arising from the same leaf axil. This suggests to us that the species is monoecious rather than dioecious.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="68D300EEDCAB567F8C38E0B8299CF0E1" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Sometimes the pedicels on staminate inflorescences are sterile. The cause of this is not clear: it may be that some male flowers are caducous or, as suggested by one of the reviewers of this manuscript, the consequence of fungal infection. A number of the pistillate inflorescences, especially on specimens with conspicuous staminate inflorescences, are very cryptic with very short peduncles. Other pistillate inflorescences have pronounced peduncles. In any case, there appears to be a bias toward collecting specimens with either staminate inflorescences or infructescences probably because these plants are more visible and manifestly fertile.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="80151EB7CB4E4569717813C99A690B58" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">
<taxonomicName id="7B81F4742C251242DF984B263BBDEE8B" authorityName="Dorr &amp; Stergios" authorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea nicholasii" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nicholasii">
<emphasis id="8BB348120298A094F028F788CD67FB1E" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Pilea nicholasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs in the Heterophyllae species group of 
<bibRefCitation id="C7744F8B98FB56B66AD4CEEEF5E4DB8B" author="Weddell, HA" journalOrPublisher="Prodromus" pageId="11" pageNumber="68" pagination="104 - 163" refId="B11" refString="Weddell, HA, 1869. Pilea. Prodromus 16 (1): 104 - 163" title="Pilea." volume="16" year="1869">Weddell (1869)</bibRefCitation>
. Its placement in one of the species groups proposed by 
<bibRefCitation id="D4BC0EDFC89123D50F32F754A428AE3F" author="Killip, EP" journalOrPublisher="Contributions from the United States National Herbarium" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" pagination="367 - 394" refId="B4" refString="Killip, EP, 1936. New species of Pilea from the Andes. Contributions from the United States National Herbarium 26 (8): 367 - 394" title="New species of Pilea from the Andes." volume="26" year="1936">Killip (1936)</bibRefCitation>
is somewhat problematic as depending upon which pair of leaves at a single node are measured 
<taxonomicName id="D9B832146C94C9B2839A0F524994BDB0" authorityName="Dorr &amp; Stergios" authorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea nicholasii" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nicholasii">
<emphasis id="CFD3CFAE31F612B0125601AA3B08D05A" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Pilea nicholasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
falls into either 
<normalizedToken id="B440D9C0FA0020B16817F1CCFCE72267" originalValue="Killip’s">Killip's</normalizedToken>
<taxonomicName id="369CED20CDC68ED243EC0C4D885737CE" genus="Centradenioideae" lsidName="" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" rank="genus">Centradenioideae</taxonomicName>
species group with major leaf laminae more than twice as long as minor leaf laminae or his Capitellatae species group with the major leaf laminae less than twice as long as the minor ones. Among species placed in the former group, 
<taxonomicName id="DB7A476C32A2683BAAAB7AD870A23988" authorityName="Dorr &amp; Stergios" authorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea nicholasii" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nicholasii">
<emphasis id="BF2C7B171CB580B0D6819CBF5521F125" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Pilea nicholasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="5EA1D54001FC169DBA9479D2E1C34EEF" authorityName="Killip" authorityYear="1936" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea hydrocotyliflora" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hydrocotyliflora">
<emphasis id="C19FBDC8F20DAB0712CB9A5CC9C7E09E" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Pilea hydrocotyliflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Killip, which was described from Colombia (Norte de Santander). However, the undersurface of the laminae is pruinose in the former and glabrous in the latter species. This makes the leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="61D6AAEBE9E3F080579B1E4DD62D89DC" authorityName="Dorr &amp; Stergios" authorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea nicholasii" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nicholasii">
<emphasis id="12CFF2C5797603C6D3D32CD524854403" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Pilea nicholasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
look lighter below than above while those of 
<taxonomicName id="73DE51B961C35B38E433F65E28591563" authorityName="Killip" authorityYear="1936" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea hydrocotyliflora" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hydrocotyliflora">
<emphasis id="E5F3BD579AF690163F3DDF29C21D32FD" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Pilea hydrocotyliflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are uniformly green. In addition, the major laminae of the former are markedly asymmetrical whereas in the latter they appear to be 
<normalizedToken id="DDCACE5280F4B74718082D66B6F14960" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
symmetrical.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB208CA1987009DF8C00557BDDB81E50" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">
<taxonomicName id="CC513FC1DC682D8C1C6D6A6B382A0EF9" authorityName="Dorr &amp; Stergios" authorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea nicholasii" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nicholasii">
<emphasis id="F8037ADDDA5F9A28F191AB74DFA7556A" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Pilea nicholasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also bears a superficial resemblance to 
<taxonomicName id="E80243D5D2B0929ECB9FEFE5817EA9E3" authorityName="Killip" authorityYear="1936" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea pichisana" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pichisana">
<emphasis id="794E57B8D153E91853FD5541BA040CA3" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Pilea pichisana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Killip, another species in the 
<taxonomicName id="7EAEDF29CD98CB92C82089A62E8A078A" genus="Centradenioideae" lsidName="" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" rank="genus">Centradenioideae</taxonomicName>
group that is known only from Peru (
<normalizedToken id="09C61CF52A09ED71C58BC89DD73BB06A" originalValue="Junín">Junin</normalizedToken>
). The major leaf laminae of 
<taxonomicName id="F1FF10E9850B9C6BB065DF181E6864F0" authorityName="Killip" authorityYear="1936" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea pichisana" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pichisana">
<emphasis id="A5574D52D238FBEA5C0C4406F5F84914" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Pilea pichisana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, are smaller than those of 
<taxonomicName id="6A1A2D0577B77D9E762EF322D94699F3" authorityName="Dorr &amp; Stergios" authorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea nicholasii" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nicholasii">
<emphasis id="01BB3F72768399F16E9A56038088C0F2" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Pilea nicholasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(2-2.8 
<normalizedToken id="944DAB294596FAE9D801118F5FC36B29" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-1.3 versus 7-9 
<normalizedToken id="2542C8D235B462BC04568EAAA224D5EC" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.4-3.2 cm) and the cystoliths are different (punctiform versus fusiform).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D9C7340CC58320C93A1004AE35C6801A" pageId="5" pageNumber="62">
<taxonomicName id="33B446DDE6F98E68F718A00A1D0CB036" authorityName="Dorr &amp; Stergios" authorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pilea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pilea nicholasii" order="Rosales" pageId="5" pageNumber="62" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nicholasii">
<emphasis id="AC1E96CDBEE1FA8FD57E3C6C1785B83B" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="62">
<pageBreakToken id="76A1FB802A63AC372ECCDC8C879916DF" pageId="5" pageNumber="62" start="start">Pilea</pageBreakToken>
nicholasii
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not appear to have any close allies in the Capitellatae species group of 
<bibRefCitation id="7823DBF57717EEE78ACA3A24ECF1F24A" author="Killip, EP" journalOrPublisher="Contributions from the United States National Herbarium" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" pagination="367 - 394" refId="B4" refString="Killip, EP, 1936. New species of Pilea from the Andes. Contributions from the United States National Herbarium 26 (8): 367 - 394" title="New species of Pilea from the Andes." volume="26" year="1936">Killip (1936)</bibRefCitation>
. It keys to a group of three species that are monoecious, but none of these three species has the pruinose undersurface of the leaf laminae found in our new species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663462DF8F2C2DF7221D91DA73923D8E" pageId="5" pageNumber="62">
